    "summary": "Objection to \"character\" — too many English senses",
    "content": "**Strongest objection to \"character\":** English polysemy. \"Character\" means moral character, literary character, written character, personality trait, and typographic glyph. In a bilingual Chinese-English philosophical text about moral concepts, at least three of those senses are live at any moment. \"All things have their character\" reads as personality. \"The Dao generates character\" is ambiguous. The reader has to disambiguate every time — and in a dense passage where 德 appears repeatedly, that friction accumulates.\n\n\"Nature\" has fewer competing senses in philosophical prose, and \"the nature of X\" is an established philosophical locution that needs no disambiguation."
